lessons.motivation:
One of the most insidious sources of undefined behavior in C++ is dangling references — references that outlive the object they point to. This bug was especially easy to write in functions returning `const T&` that accidentally create a temporary in the `return` expression.

```cpp
// Classic bug: the temporary std::string dies before the function returns,
// the caller gets a reference to a destroyed object
const std::string& get_name() {
    return std::string("Alice");  // UB before C++26 — merely a warning!
}
```

Before C++26, compilers emitted only a **warning** (`-Wreturn-local-addr`) for this code, and the program continued to compile and "run" with undefined behavior. C++26 (proposal **P2748** "Disallow Binding a Returned Glvalue to a Temporary") makes this category of mistakes **ill-formed** — code no longer compiles, and the compiler issues a hard error instead of a warning.

examples.code:
#include <print>
#include <string>

// SAFE #1: return by value (NRVO makes this efficient)
std::string get_name() {
    return std::string("Alice");
}

// SAFE #2: return reference to a long-lived (static) object
const std::string& get_static() {
    static const std::string name = "Bob";
    return name;  // OK: static lives for the entire program
}

// SAFE #3: lifetime extension — const-ref directly bound to a temporary
void demo_lifetime_extension() {
    const std::string& r = std::string("hello");  // lifetime extended
    std::print("extended: {}\n", r);  // r is valid here
}

int main() {
    std::string name = get_name();
    std::print("{}\n", name);

    const std::string& sr = get_static();
    std::print("{}\n", sr);

    demo_lifetime_extension();
}

#include <print>
#include <string>
#include <utility>

// This function just forwards the reference — does NOT extend lifetime!
const std::string& passthru(const std::string& s) { return s; }

int main() {
    // CASE 1: direct binding — lifetime IS extended (OK)
    {
        const std::string& r = std::string("direct");
        std::print("direct: {}\n", r);
    }

    // CASE 2: const auto& in structured binding — lifetime extended (OK)
    {
        auto pair_fn = [] { return std::pair<std::string, int>{"Carol", 30}; };
        const auto& [nm, age] = pair_fn();  // temp pair lifetime extended
        std::print("{} is {}\n", nm, age);
    }

    // CASE 3: reference to a long-lived variable through a function (OK)
    {
        const std::string name = "Dave";
        const std::string& ref = passthru(name);  // name outlives ref
        std::print("via func: {}\n", ref);
    }

    return 0;
}

#include <type_traits>
#include <string>
#include <print>

int main() {
    // const int& binds to a temporary int (from a prvalue)
    std::print("const int& <- int: {}\n",
        std::reference_constructs_from_temporary_v<const int&, int>);

    // const double& from int: implicit int->double creates a temporary double
    std::print("const double& <- int: {}\n",
        std::reference_constructs_from_temporary_v<const double&, int>);

    // const string& from const char*: implicit char*->string creates a temporary string
    std::print("const string& <- const char*: {}\n",
        std::reference_constructs_from_temporary_v<const std::string&, const char*>);

    // int& from int: non-const lvalue reference can't bind to a prvalue at all
    std::print("int& <- int: {}\n",
        std::reference_constructs_from_temporary_v<int&, int>);

    return 0;
}

